{"data":{"mdx":null,"markdownRemark":{"excerpt":"Clay is highly flexible, so you can use the components in different applications with frameworks such as Angular, Vue, and React. Feel freeâ€¦","timeToRead":1,"html":"<p class=\"clay-p\">Clay is highly flexible, so you can use the components in different applications with frameworks such as Angular, Vue, and React. Feel free to apply the Clay standards in your application.</p>\n<h2 class=\"clay-h2\">Introduction</h2>\n<p class=\"clay-p\"><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Web_Components\">WebComponents</a> is a web standard that is to be natively implemented in browsers in the future, so do not worry if you want to go that route. Clay gives you the ability to use the components as Custom Elements in your HTML markup.</p>\n<h2 class=\"clay-h2\">Installation</h2>\n<p class=\"clay-p\">You can start by choosing how to import your component: by <a href=\"/docs/get-started/importing-the-js-component.html\">npm</a> or <a href=\"/docs/get-started/introduction.html\">CDN</a>. You need to import the javascript of the component into your application in order for Clay to be included and rendered as a WebComponent component.</p>\n<h2 class=\"clay-h2\">Using</h2>\n<p class=\"clay-p\">Once you import your component into your application, you just use it as an HTML TAG. Consider:</p>\n<div class=\"code-container\">\n            <button class=\"btn btn-sm btn-copy\" title=\"Copy\"><svg class=\"lexicon-icon\"><use xlink:href=\"/images/icons/icons.svg#paste\"></use></svg></button>\n            <div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"html\"><pre class=\"gatsby-code-html\"><code class=\"gatsby-code-html\"><span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token punctuation\">&lt;</span>clay-button</span> <span class=\"token attr-name\">label</span><span class=\"token attr-value\"><span class=\"token punctuation\">=</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">\"</span>Primary<span class=\"token punctuation\">\"</span></span> <span class=\"token attr-name\">type</span><span class=\"token attr-value\"><span class=\"token punctuation\">=</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">\"</span>button<span class=\"token punctuation\">\"</span></span><span class=\"token punctuation\">></span></span><span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token tag\"><span class=\"token punctuation\">&lt;/</span>clay-button</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">></span></span></code></pre></div>\n        </div>\n<h2 class=\"clay-h2\">Examples</h2>\n<p class=\"clay-p\">We have created some example use cases in applications for <code class=\"gatsby-code-text\">React</code>, <code class=\"gatsby-code-text\">Vue</code>, and <code class=\"gatsby-code-text\">Angular</code> for you to follow.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://github.com/liferay/clay/tree/master/examples/angular-with-clay\">Angular</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://github.com/liferay/clay/tree/master/examples/react-with-clay\">React</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://github.com/liferay/clay/tree/master/examples/vue-with-clay\">Vue</a></li>\n</ul>","htmlAst":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{"className":["clay-p"]},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Clay is highly flexible, so you can use the components in different applications with frameworks such as Angular, Vue, and React. Feel free to apply the Clay standards in your application."}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"h2","properties":{"className":["clay-h2"]},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Introduction"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{"className":["clay-p"]},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"a","properties":{"href":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Web_Components"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"WebComponents"}]},{"type":"text","value":" is a web standard that is to be natively implemented in browsers in the future, so do not worry if you want to go that route. Clay gives you 